    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix integer overflow in polar decoder path metric computation\n\n### Summary\nThere is an integer overflow leading to incorrect computation in the polar decoder when processing path metrics. The issue occurs in `updatePathMetric()` and related functions when list size approaches maximum values, causing wraparound in loop counters.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/PHY/CODING/nrPolar_tools/nr_polar_decoding_tools.c`: Changed loop variable types from `uint` to `uint8_t` in all functions where the bound is `listSize` (uint8_t) to prevent signed/unsigned comparison issues\n- Updated `updateBit()`, `updateLLR()`, `updatePathMetric()`, and `updatePathMetric2()` functions\n- Changed `bitValue` type from `uint` to `uint8_t` in `updatePathMetric2()` for consistency\n\n### Reproduction\nWhen running polar decoding with maximum list size (255), the decoder may produce incorrect results or crash due to integer overflow in loop counters. Symptoms include:\n- Incorrect decoded output for valid input\n- Segmentation fault during decoding\n- Path metric computations returning infinity or NaN values\n\nThe issue is most likely to occur when `listSize` is at maximum values and the loop variables are compared against bounds of different integer types.\n"
}